# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aiohttp-client
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] Input and output operations on a computer can be extremely slow compared to the processing of data.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] An I/O device can incorporate mechanical devices that must physically move, such as a hard drive seeking a track to read or write; this is often orders of magnitude slower than the switching of electric current.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] For example, during a disk operation that takes ten milliseconds to perform, a processor that is clocked at one gigahertz could have performed ten million instruction-processing cycles.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] A simple approach to I/O would be to start the access and then wait for it to complete.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] But such an approach, called **synchronous I/O** or **blocking I/O**, would block the progress of a program while the communication is in progress, leaving system resources idle.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] When a program makes many I/O operations (such as a program mainly or largely dependent on user input), this means that the processor can spend almost all of its time idle waiting for I/O operations to complete.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] Alternatively, it is possible to start the communication and then perform processing that does not require that the I/O be completed.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] This approach is called asynchronous input/output.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] Many operating system functions exist to implement asynchronous I/O at many levels.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] In fact, one of the main functions of all but the most rudimentary of operating systems is to perform at least some form of basic asynchronous I/O, though this may not be particularly apparent to the user or the programmer.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] In the simplest software solution, the hardware device status is polled at intervals to detect whether the device is ready for its next operation.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] (For example, the CP/M operating system was built this way.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] Multitasking operating systems can exploit the functionality provided by hardware interrupts, whilst hiding the complexity of interrupt handling from the user.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] Spooling was one of the first forms of multitasking designed to exploit asynchronous I/O.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] Finally, multithreading and explicit asynchronous I/O APIs within user processes can exploit asynchronous I/O further, at the cost of extra software complexity.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] Asynchronous I/O is used to improve energy efficiency, and in some cases throughput.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] However, it can have negative effects on latency and throughput in some cases.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] All forms of asynchronous I/O open applications up to potential resource conflicts and associated failure.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] Careful programming (often using mutual exclusion, semaphores, etc.) is required to prevent this.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] When exposing asynchronous I/O to applications there are a few broad classes of implementation.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] The form of the API provided to the application does not necessarily correspond with the mechanism actually provided by the operating system; emulations are possible.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] Furthermore, more than one method may be used by a single application, depending on its needs and the desires of its programmer(s).
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] Many operating systems provide more than one of these mechanisms, it is possible that some may provide all of them.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] In a multitasking operating system, processing can be distributed across different processes, which run independently, have their own memory, and process their own I/O flows; these flows are typically connected in pipelines.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] Processes are fairly expensive to create and maintain, so this solution only works well if the set of processes is small and relatively stable.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] It also assumes that the individual processes can operate independently, apart from processing each other's I/O; if they need to communicate in other ways, coordinating them can become difficult.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] An extension of this approach is dataflow programming, which allows more complicated networks than just the chains that pipes support.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] Polling provides non-blocking synchronous API which may be used to implement some asynchronous API.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] Available in traditional Unix and Windows.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] Its major problem is that it can waste CPU time polling repeatedly when there is nothing else for the issuing process to do, reducing the time available for other processes.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] Also, because a polling application is essentially single-threaded it may be unable to fully exploit I/O parallelism that the hardware is capable of.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] Available in BSD Unix, and almost anything else with a TCP/IP protocol stack that either utilizes or is modeled after the BSD implementation.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] A variation on the theme of polling, a select loop uses the `select` system call to sleep until a condition occurs on a file descriptor (e.g., when data is available for reading), a timeout occurs, or a signal is received (e.g., when a child process dies).
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] By examining the return parameters of the `select` call, the loop finds out which file descriptor has changed and executes the appropriate code.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] Often, for ease of use, the select loop is implemented as an event loop, perhaps using callback functions; the situation lends itself particularly well to event-driven programming.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] While this method is reliable and relatively efficient, it depends heavily on the Unix paradigm that "everything is a file"; any blocking I/O that does not involve a file descriptor will block the process.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] The select loop also relies on being able to involve all I/O in the central `select` call; libraries that conduct their own I/O are particularly problematic in this respect.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] Some Unixes provide system-specific calls with better scaling; for example, `epoll` in Linux (that fills the return selection array with only those event sources on which an event has occurred), `kqueue` in FreeBSD, and event ports (and `/dev/poll`) in Solaris.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] SVR3 Unix provided the `poll` system call.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] Arguably better-named than `select`, for the purposes of this discussion it is essentially the same thing.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] SVR4 Unixes (and thus POSIX) offer both calls.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] I/O is issued asynchronously, and when it is completed a signal (interrupt) is generated.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] As in low-level kernel programming, the facilities available for safe use within the signal handler are limited, and the main flow of the process could have been interrupted at nearly any point, resulting in inconsistent data structures as seen by the signal handler.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] The signal handler is usually not able to issue further asynchronous I/O by itself.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] The *signal* approach, though relatively simple to implement within the OS, brings to the application program the unwelcome baggage associated with writing an operating system's kernel interrupt system.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] Its worst characteristic is that *every* blocking (synchronous) system call is potentially interruptible; the programmer must usually incorporate retry code at each call.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] Available in the classic Mac OS, VMS and Windows.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] Bears many of the characteristics of the *signal* method as it is fundamentally the same thing, though rarely recognized as such.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] The difference is that each I/O request usually can have its own completion function, whereas the *signal* system has a single callback.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] On the other hand, a potential problem of using callbacks is that stack depth can grow unmanageably, as an extremely common thing to do when one I/O is finished is to schedule another.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] If this should be satisfied immediately, the first callback is not 'unwound' off the stack before the next one is invoked.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] Systems to prevent this (like 'mid-ground' scheduling of new work) add complexity and reduce performance.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] In practice, however, this is generally not a problem because the new I/O will itself usually return as soon as the new I/O is started allowing the stack to be 'unwound'.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] The problem can also be prevented by avoiding any further callbacks, by means of a queue, until the first callback returns.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] Light-weight processes (LWPs) or threads are available in most modern operating systems.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] Like the *process* method, but with lower overhead and without the data isolation that hampers coordination of the flows.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] Each LWP or thread itself uses traditional blocking synchronous I/O, which simplifies programming logic; this is a common paradigm used in many programming languages including Java and Rust.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] Multithreading needs to use kernel-provided synchronization mechanisms and thread-safe libraries.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] This method is most suitable for extremely large-scale applications like web servers due to the large numbers of threads needed.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] This approach is also used in the Erlang programming language runtime system.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] The Erlang virtual machine uses asynchronous I/O using a small pool of only a few threads or sometimes just one process, to handle I/O from up to millions of Erlang processes.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] I/O handling in each process is written mostly using blocking synchronous I/O.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] This way high performance of asynchronous I/O is merged with simplicity of normal I/O (cf. the Actor model).
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] Many I/O problems in Erlang are mapped to message passing, which can be easily processed using built-in selective receive.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] Fibers / Coroutines can be viewed as a similarly lightweight approach to do asynchronous I/O outside of the Erlang runtime system, although they do not provide exactly the same guarantees as Erlang processes.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] Available in Microsoft Windows, Solaris, AmigaOS, DNIX and Linux (using io_uring, available on 5.1 and above).
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] I/O requests are issued asynchronously, but notifications of completion are provided via a synchronizing queue mechanism in the order they are completed.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] Usually associated with a state-machine structuring of the main process (event-driven programming), which can bear little resemblance to a process that does not use asynchronous I/O or that uses one of the other forms, hampering code reuse.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] Does not require additional special synchronization mechanisms or thread-safe libraries, nor are the textual (code) and time (event) flows separated.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] Available in VMS and AmigaOS (often used in conjunction with a completion port).
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] Bears many of the characteristics of the *completion queue* method, as it is essentially a completion queue of depth one.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] To simulate the effect of queue 'depth', an additional event flag is required for each potential unprocessed (but completed) event, or event information can be lost.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] Waiting for the next available event in such a clump requires synchronizing mechanisms that may not scale well to larger numbers of potentially parallel events.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] Available in mainframes by IBM, Groupe Bull, and Unisys.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] Channel I/O is designed to maximize CPU utilization and throughput by offloading most I/O onto a coprocessor.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] The coprocessor has onboard DMA, handles device interrupts, is controlled by the main CPU, and only interrupts the main CPU when it's truly necessary.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] This architecture also supports so-called channel programs that run on the channel processor to do heavy lifting for I/O activities and protocols.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] Available in Windows Server 2012 and Windows 8.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] Optimized for applications that process large numbers of small messages to achieve higher I/O operations per second with reduced jitter and latency.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] The vast majority of general-purpose computing hardware relies entirely upon two methods of implementing asynchronous I/O: polling and interrupts.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] Usually both methods are used together, the balance depends heavily upon the design of the hardware and its required performance characteristics.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] Pure polling systems are entirely possible, small microcontrollers (such as systems using the PIC microcontroller) are often built this way.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] CP/M systems could also be built this way (though rarely were), with or without DMA.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] Also, when the utmost performance is necessary for only a *few* tasks, at the expense of any other potential tasks, polling may also be appropriate as the overhead of taking interrupts may be unwelcome.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] Most general-purpose computing systems rely heavily upon interrupts.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] A pure interrupt system may be possible, though usually some component of polling is also required, as it is very common for multiple potential sources of interrupts to share a common interrupt signal line, in which case polling is used within the device driver to resolve the actual source.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] (This resolution time also contributes to an interrupt system's performance penalty.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] Over the years a great deal of work has been done to try to minimize the overhead associated with servicing an interrupt.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] Hybrid approaches are also possible, wherein an interrupt can trigger the beginning of some burst of asynchronous I/O, and polling is used within the burst itself.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] This technique is common in high-speed device drivers, such as network or disk, where the time lost in returning to the pre-interrupt task is greater than the time until the next required servicing.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] (Common I/O hardware in use these days relies heavily upon DMA and large data buffers to make up for a relatively poorly-performing interrupt system.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] These characteristically use polling inside the driver loops, and can exhibit tremendous throughput.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] At one time this sort of hybrid approach was common in disk and network drivers where there was not DMA or significant buffering available.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] (In effect using the processor itself as a DMA engine.) The 6502 processor offered an unusual means to provide a three-element per-datum loop, as it had a hardware pin that, when asserted, would cause the processor's Overflow bit to be set directly.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] Using only these two tools (polling, and interrupts), all the other forms of asynchronous I/O discussed above may be (and in fact, are) synthesized.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] In an environment such as a Java virtual machine (JVM), asynchronous I/O can be synthesized *even though* the environment the JVM is running in may not offer it at all.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] This is due to the interpreted nature of the JVM.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] The JVM may poll (or take an interrupt) periodically to institute an internal flow of control change, effecting the appearance of multiple simultaneous processes, at least some of which presumably exist in order to perform asynchronous I/O.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] That, in fact, is the problem with using polling in any form to synthesize a different form of asynchronous I/O.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] Every CPU cycle that is a poll is wasted, and lost to overhead rather than accomplishing a desired task.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] Every CPU cycle that is *not* a poll represents an increase in latency of reaction to pending I/O.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] Striking an acceptable balance between these two opposing forces is difficult.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] The trick to maximize efficiency is to minimize the amount of work that has to be done upon reception of an interrupt in order to awaken the appropriate application.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] Secondarily (but perhaps no less important) is the method the application itself uses to determine what it needs to do.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] Particularly problematic (for application efficiency) are the exposed polling methods, including the select/poll mechanisms.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] Though the underlying I/O events they are interested in are in all likelihood interrupt-driven, the interaction *to* this mechanism is polled and can consume a large amount of time in the poll.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] This is particularly true of the potentially large-scale polling possible through select (and poll).
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] Interrupts map very well to Signals, Callback functions, Completion Queues, and Event flags, such systems can be very efficient.
[src:aiohttp-client/asynchronous-i-o] The following examples show three approaches to reading I/O.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] This page gives a good introduction in how to get started with aiohttp client API.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] Let’s get started with some simple examples.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] Now, we have a `ClientSession` called `session` and a `ClientResponse` object called `resp`.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] We can get all the information we need from the response.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] The mandatory parameter of `ClientSession.get()` coroutine is an HTTP *url* (`str` or class:*yarl.URL* instance).
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] To make several requests to the same site more simple, the parameter `base_url` of `ClientSession` constructor can be used.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] Most likely you need a session per application which performs all requests together.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] More complex cases may require a session per site, e.g. one for Github and other one for Facebook APIs.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] Anyway making a session for every request is a **very bad** idea.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] A session contains a connection pool inside.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] Connection reusage and keep-alive (both are on by default) may speed up total performance.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] You often want to send some sort of data in the URL’s query string.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] If you were constructing the URL by hand, this data would be given as key/value pairs in the URL after a question mark, e.g.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] `httpbin.org/get?key=val`. aiohttp allows you to provide these arguments as a `dict`, using the `params` keyword argument.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] You can see that the URL has been correctly encoded by printing the URL.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] For sending data with multiple values for the same key `MultiDict` may be used; the library support nested lists (`{'key': ['value1', 'value2']}`) alternative as well.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] You can also pass `str` content as param.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] The value is used as a query string, but passing `params` does not disable URL canonicalization.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] Canonicalization encodes *host* part by IDNA codec and applies requoting to *path* and *query* parts.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] Sometimes canonicalization is not desirable if server accepts exact representation and does not requote URL itself.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] Passing *params* overrides `encoded=True`.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] Never use both options if you need to preserve exact query-string bytes.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] Build the full URL (including query) instead.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] We can read the content of the server’s response and its status code.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] `aiohttp` automatically decodes the content from the server.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] The `gzip` and `deflate` transfer-encodings are automatically decoded for you.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] You can enable `brotli` transfer-encodings support, just install Brotli or brotlicffi.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] You can enable `zstd` transfer-encodings support, install backports.zstd.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] If you are using Python >= 3.14, no dependency should be required.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] By default session uses python’s standard `json` module for serialization.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] But it is possible to use a different `serializer`.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] `orjson` library is faster than standard `json` and is actively maintained.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] Since `orjson.dumps` returns `bytes`, pass it via the `json_serialize_bytes` parameter to avoid unnecessary encoding/decoding overhead.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] In case that JSON decoding fails, `json()` will raise an exception.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] It is possible to specify custom encoding and decoder functions for the `json()` call.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] The methods above reads the whole response body into memory.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] If you are planning on reading lots of data, consider using the streaming response method documented below.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] While methods `read()`, `json()` and `text()` are very convenient you should use them carefully.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] All these methods load the whole response in memory.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] For example if you want to download several gigabyte sized files, these methods will load all the data in memory.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] Instead you can use the `content` attribute.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] It is an instance of the `aiohttp.StreamReader` class.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] It is not possible to use `read()`, `json()` and `text()` after explicit reading from `content`.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] Typically, you want to send some form-encoded data – much like an HTML form.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] To do this, simply pass a dictionary to the *data* argument.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] If you want to send data that is not form-encoded you can do it by passing a `bytes` instead of a `dict`.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] If you pass a file object as data parameter, aiohttp will stream it to the server automatically.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] Check `StreamReader` for supported format information.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] `aiohttp` supports multiple types of streaming uploads, which allows you to send large files without reading them into memory.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] Async generators and other non-rewindable data sources (such as `StreamReader`) cannot be replayed if a redirect occurs (for example, HTTP 307 or 308).
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] If the request body has already been streamed, `aiohttp` raises `ClientPayloadError`.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] Python 3.5 has no native support for asynchronous generators, use `async_generator` library as workaround.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] Deprecated since version 3.1: `aiohttp` still supports `aiohttp.streamer` decorator but this approach is deprecated in favor of *asynchronous generators* as shown above.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] `aiohttp` works with client websockets out-of-the-box.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] You have to use the `aiohttp.ClientSession.ws_connect()` coroutine for client websocket connection.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] You **must** use the only websocket task for both reading (e.g.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] `await ws.receive()` or `async for msg in ws:`) and writing but may have multiple writer tasks which can only send data asynchronously (by `await ws.send_str('data')` for example).
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] Timeout settings are stored in `ClientTimeout` data structure.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] By default *aiohttp* uses a *total* 300 seconds (5min) timeout, it means that the whole operation should finish in 5 minutes.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] In order to allow time for DNS fallback, the default `sock_connect` timeout is 30 seconds.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] All fields are floats, `None` or `0` disables a particular timeout check, see the `ClientTimeout` reference for defaults and additional details.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] The ceiling is done for the sake of optimization, when many concurrent tasks are scheduled to wake-up at the almost same but different absolute times.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] It leads to very many event loop wakeups, which kills performance.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] The optimization shifts absolute wakeup times by scheduling them to exactly the same time as other neighbors, the loop wakes up once-per-second for timeout expiration.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] Smaller timeouts are not rounded to help testing; in the real life network timeouts usually greater than tens of seconds.
[src:aiohttp-client/client-quickstart] However, the default threshold value of 5 seconds can be configured using the `ceil_threshold` parameter.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] In software, an **event loop** is an algorithm that continually dispatches control flow for events.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] The loop requests the next event from an event provider (which generally blocks the loop until an event occurs), and when an event is received, invokes its associated event handler.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] When the event loop is the central event dispatcher of a program, as it often is, it is called the **main loop** or **main event loop**.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] In modern environments such as web browsers and server runtimes, the event loop is a fundamental mechanism that enables asynchronous execution by continuously monitoring and dispatching events or messages from a queue when the main program thread is idle.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] In JavaScript, the event loop allows non-blocking handling of tasks such as user interactions, timers, and I/O operations despite the language being single-threaded.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] The same algorithm can be used to process inbound messages, a superset of events.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] In this context, the algorithm is called a **message loop**, **message dispatcher**, or **message pump**.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] A common use for a message loop is message passing inter-process communication where the message queue is maintained outside of the program (such as by the operating system).
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] Typically, a program that operates in a graphical user interface (GUI) environment uses an event loop, and due to the predominance of GUI environments, most modern applications have a main event loop.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] In the following pseudocode, `get_next_message()` is a placeholder for a function that is typically provided by the operating system that blocks until a message is available.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] Thus, the loop only repeats when there is a message to process.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] Many programs include an event loop in the high-level design; a main event loop, but there are alternative designs.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] A program can exit as soon as it completes the actions that it's designed to do without external (i.e. user) interaction.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] Often, such a program has optional behavior that is set up before the program starts such as via the command-line interface (CLI) or environment variables.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] Utility software is often of this nature.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] Even if a program provides for user interaction, it might not use an event loop.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] A program that provides an internal CLI does include a command processor that is similar to an event loop in that it dispatches to command handlers based on user input.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] A web page and its JavaScript typically run in a single-threaded web browser process.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] The browser process deals with messages from a queue one at a time.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] A JavaScript function or another browser event might be associated with a given message.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] When the browser process has finished with a message, it proceeds to the next message in the queue.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] In JavaScript environments, the event loop works with separate queues — including a task queue and a microtask queue — to manage asynchronous operations such as timers, promise callbacks, and DOM events.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] When the call stack is empty, the event loop selects the next task from these queues to execute.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] In Windows, a process that interacts with the user must accept and react to incoming messages, which is almost inevitably done by a message loop in that process.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] In Windows, a message is equated to an event created and imposed upon the operating system.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] An event can be user interaction, network traffic, system processing, timer activity, inter-process communication, among others.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] For non-interactive, I/O only events, Windows has I/O completion ports.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] I/O completion port loops run separately from the Message loop, and do not interact with the Message loop out of the box.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] The heart of most Win32 applications is the WinMain() function, which calls GetMessage() in a loop.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] GetMessage() blocks until a message (event), is received (with function PeekMessage() as a non-blocking alternative).
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] After some optional processing, it will call DispatchMessage(), which dispatches the message to the relevant handler, also known as WindowProc.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] Normally, messages that have no special WindowProc() are dispatched to DefWindowProc, the default one.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] DispatchMessage() calls the WindowProc of the HWND handle of the message (registered with the RegisterClass() function).
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] More recent versions of Windows guarantee that messages will be delivered to an application's message loop in the order that they were perceived by the system and its peripherals.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] This guarantee is essential when considering the design consequences of multithreaded applications.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] However, some messages have different rules, such as messages that are always received last, or messages with a different documented priority.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] X applications using Xlib directly are built around the `XNextEvent` family of functions; `XNextEvent` blocks until an event appears on the event queue, whereupon the application processes it appropriately.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] The Xlib event loop only handles window system events; applications that need to be able to wait on other files and devices could construct their own event loop from primitives such as `ConnectionNumber`, but in practice tend to use multithreading.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] In the more common case, GUI toolkits based on Xlib usually support adding events.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] For example, toolkits based on Xt Intrinsics have `XtAppAddInput()` and `XtAppAddTimeout()`.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] It is not safe to call Xlib functions from a signal handler, because the X application may have been interrupted in an arbitrary state, e.g. within `XNextEvent`.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] See [1] for a solution for X11R5, X11R6 and Xt.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] The GLib event loop was originally created for use in GTK but is now used in non-GUI applications as well, such as D-Bus.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] The resource polled is the collection of file descriptors the application is interested in; the polling block will be interrupted if a signal arrives or a timeout expires (e.g. if the application has specified a timeout or idle task).
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] Application libraries that are built on the GLib event loop include GStreamer and the asynchronous I/O methods of GnomeVFS, but GTK remains the most visible client library.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] Events from the windowing system (in X, read off the X socket) are translated by GDK into GTK events and emitted as GLib signals on the application's widget objects.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] Exactly one CFRunLoop is allowed per thread, and arbitrarily many sources and observers can be attached.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] Sources then communicate with observers through the run loop, with it organising queueing and dispatch of messages.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] The CFRunLoop is abstracted in Cocoa as an NSRunLoop, which allows any message (equivalent to a function call in non-reflective runtimes) to be queued for dispatch to any object.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] In Unix, the everything is a file paradigm leads to a file-based event loop.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] Reading from and writing to files, inter-process communication, network communication, and device control are all achieved using file I/O, with the target identified by a file descriptor.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] The select and poll system calls allow a set of file descriptors to be monitored for a change of state, e.g. when data becomes available to be read.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] In Unix, a signal is an asynchronous event that is handled by a signal handler which runs while the rest of the task is suspended.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] If a signal is received and handled while the task is blocking in `select()`, select will return early with EINTR; if a signal is received while the task is CPU bound, the task will be suspended between instructions until the signal handler returns.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] A way to handle a signal is for signal handlers to set a global flag and have the event loop check for the flag immediately before and after the `select()` call; if it is set, handle the signal in the same manner as with events on file descriptors.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] Unfortunately, this gives rise to a race condition: if a signal arrives immediately between checking the flag and calling `select()`, it will not be handled until `select()` returns for some other reason (for example, being interrupted by a frustrated user).
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] The solution arrived at by POSIX is the `pselect()` call, which is similar to `select()` but takes an additional `sigmask` parameter, which describes a *signal mask*.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] This allows an application to mask signals in the main task, then remove the mask for the duration of the `select()` call such that signal handlers are only called while the application is I/O bound.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] However, implementations of `pselect()` have not always been reliable; versions of Linux prior to 2.6.16 do not have a `pselect()` system call, forcing glibc to emulate it via a method prone to the very same race condition `pselect()` is intended to avoid.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] An alternative, more portable solution, is to convert asynchronous events to file-based events using the *self-pipe trick*, where "a signal handler writes a byte to a pipe whose other end is monitored by `select()` in the main program".
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] In Linux kernel version 2.6.22, a new system call `signalfd()` was added, which allows receiving signals via a special file descriptor.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] In environments such as web browsers and Node.js, the event loop is central to asynchronous program behavior.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] JavaScript runs on a single thread for execution, but host environments provide APIs for non-blocking operations, such as timers, network requests, and user events.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] Completed asynchronous operations are placed in queues, and the event loop repeatedly checks whether the call stack is empty to schedule queued callbacks.
[src:aiohttp-client/event-loop] This enables JavaScript applications to remain responsive while handling multiple asynchronous tasks.
[src:aiohttp-client/http-persistent-connection] Under HTTP 1.0, connections should always be **closed** by the server after sending the response.
[src:aiohttp-client/http-persistent-connection] Since at least late 1995, developers of popular products (browsers, web servers, etc.) using HTTP/1.0, started to add an unofficial extension (to the protocol) named "keep-alive" in order to allow the reuse of a connection for multiple requests/responses.
[src:aiohttp-client/http-persistent-connection] When the server receives this request and generates a response, if it supports keep-alive then it also adds the same above header to the response.
[src:aiohttp-client/http-persistent-connection] Following this, the connection is not dropped, but is instead kept open.
[src:aiohttp-client/http-persistent-connection] When the client sends another request, it uses the same connection.
[src:aiohttp-client/http-persistent-connection] After that the connection is closed following specified rules.
[src:aiohttp-client/http-persistent-connection] Since 1997, the various versions of HTTP/1.1 specifications acknowledged the usage of this unofficial extension and included a few caveats regarding the interoperability between HTTP/1.0 (keep-alive) and HTTP/1.1 clients / servers.
[src:aiohttp-client/http-persistent-connection] In HTTP 1.1, all connections are considered persistent unless declared otherwise.
[src:aiohttp-client/http-persistent-connection] The HTTP **persistent connections** do not use separate keepalive messages, they just allow multiple requests to use a single connection.
[src:aiohttp-client/http-persistent-connection] However, the default connection timeout of Apache httpd 1.3 and 2.0 is as little as 15 seconds and just 5 seconds for Apache httpd 2.2 and above.
[src:aiohttp-client/http-persistent-connection] The advantage of a short timeout is the ability to deliver multiple components of a web page quickly while not consuming resources to run multiple server processes or threads for too long.
[src:aiohttp-client/http-persistent-connection] Keepalive makes it difficult for the client to determine where one response ends and the next response begins, particularly during pipelined HTTP operation.
[src:aiohttp-client/http-persistent-connection] This is a serious problem when `Content-Length` cannot be used due to streaming.
[src:aiohttp-client/http-persistent-connection] To solve this problem, HTTP 1.1 introduced a chunked transfer coding that defines a `last-chunk` bit.
[src:aiohttp-client/http-persistent-connection] The `last-chunk` bit is set at the end of each response so that the client knows where the next response begins.
[src:aiohttp-client/http-persistent-connection] According to RFC 7230, section 6.4, "a client ought to limit the number of simultaneous open connections that it maintains to a given server".
[src:aiohttp-client/http-persistent-connection] The previous version of the HTTP/1.1 specification stated specific maximum values but in the words of RFC 7230 "this was found to be impractical for many applications... instead... be conservative when opening multiple connections".
[src:aiohttp-client/http-persistent-connection] These guidelines are intended to improve HTTP response times and avoid congestion.
[src:aiohttp-client/http-persistent-connection] If HTTP pipelining is correctly implemented, there is no performance benefit to be gained from additional connections, while additional connections may cause issues with congestion.
[src:aiohttp-client/http-persistent-connection] If the client does not close the connection when all of the data it needs has been received, the resources needed to keep the connection open on the server will be unavailable for other clients.
[src:aiohttp-client/http-persistent-connection] This affects both server's availability and the availability of resources on the server, with the degree of impact depending on the server's architecture and configuration.
[src:aiohttp-client/http-persistent-connection] Also a race condition can occur where the client sends a request to the server at the same time that the server closes the TCP connection.
[src:aiohttp-client/http-persistent-connection] A server should send a 408 Request Timeout status code to the client immediately before closing the connection.
[src:aiohttp-client/http-persistent-connection] When a client receives the 408 status code, after having sent the request, it may open a new connection to the server and re-send the request.
[src:aiohttp-client/http-persistent-connection] Not all clients will re-send the request, and many that do will only do so if the request has an idempotent HTTP method.
[src:aiohttp-client/http-persistent-connection] All modern web browsers including Chrome, Edge, Firefox, Opera (since 4.0), and Safari use persistent connections.
[src:aiohttp-client/http-persistent-connection] In Firefox, the number of simultaneous connections can be customized (per-server, per-proxy, total).
[src:aiohttp-client/http-persistent-connection] Persistent connections time out after 115 seconds (1.92 minutes) of inactivity which is changeable via the configuration.
[src:aiohttp-client/http-persistent-connection] Python's `requests` library contains `requests.Session()`, which establishes a persistent HTTP connection, thereby allowing the underlying TCP connection to be reused, which can result in a significant performance increase.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-quickstart] In order to implement a web server, first create a request handler.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-quickstart] Now, head over to `http://localhost:8080/` to see the results.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-quickstart] Both ways essentially do the same work, the difference is only in your taste: do you prefer *Django style* with famous `urls.py` or *Flask* with shiny route decorators.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-quickstart] Graceful shutdown section explains what `run_app()` does and how to implement complex server initialization/finalization from scratch.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-quickstart] Application runners for more handling more complex cases like *asynchronous* web application serving and multiple hosts support.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-quickstart] For local development we typically recommend using aiohttp-devtools.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-quickstart] A request handler must be a coroutine that accepts a `Request` instance as its only argument and returns a `StreamResponse` derived (e.g.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-quickstart] The *HTTP method* can be queried later in the request handler using the `aiohttp.web.BaseRequest.method` property.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-quickstart] By default endpoints added with `GET` method will accept `HEAD` requests and return the same response headers as they would for a `GET` request.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-quickstart] Here `handler` won’t be called on `HEAD` request and the server will respond with `405: Method Not Allowed`.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-quickstart] Peer disconnection section explains how handlers behave when a client connection drops and ways to optimize handling of this.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-quickstart] Internally routes are served by `Application.router` (`UrlDispatcher` instance).
[src:aiohttp-client/web-quickstart] Resource is an entry in *route table* which corresponds to requested URL.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-quickstart] Resource in turn has at least one *route*.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-quickstart] Route corresponds to handling *HTTP method* by calling *web handler*.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-quickstart] Thus when you add a *route* the *resource* object is created under the hood.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-quickstart] The library implementation **merges** all subsequent route additions for the same path adding the only resource for all HTTP methods.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-quickstart] For instance, a resource with the path `'/a/{name}/c'` would match all incoming requests with paths such as `'/a/b/c'`, `'/a/1/c'`, and `'/a/etc/c'`.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-quickstart] A variable *part* is specified in the form `{identifier}`, where the `identifier` can be used later in a request handler to access the matched value for that *part*.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-quickstart] By default, each *part* matches the regular expression `[^{}/]+`.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-quickstart] But sometimes it’s convenient to group logically similar handlers into a Python *class*.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-quickstart] `aiohttp.web` has support for *class based views*.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-quickstart] Handlers should be coroutines accepting *self* only and returning response object as regular web-handler.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-quickstart] Request object can be retrieved by `View.request` property.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-quickstart] Example will process GET and POST requests for */path/to* but raise *405 Method not allowed* exception for unimplemented HTTP methods.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-quickstart] Code examples shown above use *imperative* style for adding new routes: they call `app.router.add_get(...)` etc.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-quickstart] There are two alternatives: route tables and route decorators.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-quickstart] The snippet calls `add_routes()` to register a list of *route definitions* (`aiohttp.web.RouteDef` instances) created by `aiohttp.web.get()` or `aiohttp.web.post()` functions.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-quickstart] The example creates a `aiohttp.web.RouteTableDef` container first.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-quickstart] The container is a list-like object with additional decorators `aiohttp.web.RouteTableDef.get()`, `aiohttp.web.RouteTableDef.post()` etc. for registering new routes.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-quickstart] After filling the container `add_routes()` is used for adding registered *route definitions* into application’s router.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-quickstart] All tree ways (imperative calls, route tables and decorators) are equivalent, you could use what do you prefer or even mix them on your own.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-quickstart] The shortcut method returns `aiohttp.web.Response` instance so you can for example set cookies before returning it from handler.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-quickstart] Often you need a container for storing user data across requests.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-quickstart] The concept is usually called a *session*.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-quickstart] HTTP Forms are supported out of the box.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-quickstart] If form’s method is `"GET"` (`<form method="get">`) use `aiohttp.web.BaseRequest.query` for getting form data.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-quickstart] To access form data with `"POST"` method use `aiohttp.web.BaseRequest.post()` or `aiohttp.web.BaseRequest.multipart()`.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-quickstart] `aiohttp.web.BaseRequest.post()` accepts both `'application/x-www-form-urlencoded'` and `'multipart/form-data'` form’s data encoding (e.g.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-quickstart] `<form enctype="multipart/form-data">`).
[src:aiohttp-client/web-quickstart] It stores files data in temporary directory.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-quickstart] If *client_max_size* is specified *post* raises *ValueError* exception.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-quickstart] For efficiency use `aiohttp.web.BaseRequest.multipart()`, It is especially effective for uploading large files (File Uploads).
[src:aiohttp-client/web-quickstart] `aiohttp.web` has built-in support for handling files uploaded from the browser.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-quickstart] First, make sure that the HTML `<form>` element has its *enctype* attribute set to `enctype="multipart/form-data"`.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-quickstart] Then, in the request handler you can access the file input field as a `FileField` instance.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-quickstart] You might have noticed a big warning in the example above.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-quickstart] The general issue is that `aiohttp.web.BaseRequest.post()` reads the whole payload in memory, resulting in possible OOM errors.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-quickstart] `aiohttp.web` supports *WebSockets* out-of-the-box.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-quickstart] `aiohttp.web` defines a set of exceptions for every *HTTP status code*.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-quickstart] Returning `HTTPException` or its subclasses is deprecated and will be removed in subsequent aiohttp versions.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-quickstart] Each exception class has a status code according to **RFC 2068**: codes with 100-300 are not really errors; 400s are client errors, and 500s are server errors.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-quickstart] If not directly specified, *headers* will be added to the *default response headers*.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-quickstart] where *location* is value for *Location HTTP header*.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] A **web server** is computer software that accepts requests via HTTP (the network protocol created to distribute web content) or its secure variant HTTPS.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] A user agent, commonly a web browser or web crawler, initiates communication by making a request for a web page or other resource using HTTP, and the server responds with the content of that resource or an error message.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] A web server can also accept and store resources sent from the user agent if configured to do so.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] The hardware used to run a web server can vary according to the volume of requests that it needs to handle.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] At the low end of the range are embedded systems, such as a router that runs a small web server as its configuration interface.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] A high-traffic Internet website might handle requests with hundreds of servers that run on racks of high-speed computers.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] A resource sent from a web server can be a pre-existing file (static content) available to the web server, or it can be generated at the time of the request (dynamic content) by another program that communicates with the server software.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] The former usually can be served faster and can be more easily cached for repeated requests, while the latter supports a broader range of applications.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] Technologies such as REST and SOAP, which use HTTP as a basis for general computer-to-computer communication, as well as support for WebDAV extensions, have extended the application of web servers well beyond their original purpose of serving human-readable pages.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] In March 1989, Sir Tim Berners-Lee proposed a new project to his employer CERN, with the goal of easing the exchange of information between scientists by using a hypertext system.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] The proposal titled *"HyperText and CERN"*, asked for comments and it was read by several people.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] In October 1990 the proposal was reformulated and enriched (having as co-author Robert Cailliau), and finally, it was approved.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] Those early browsers retrieved web pages written in a simple early form of HTML from web servers using a new basic communication protocol that was named HTTP 0.9.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] In August 1991 Tim Berners-Lee announced the *birth of WWW technology* and encouraged scientists to adopt and develop it.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] Soon after, those programs, along with their source code, were made available to people interested in their usage.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] Although the source code was not formally licensed or placed in the public domain, CERN informally allowed users and developers to experiment and further develop on top of them.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] Berners-Lee started promoting the adoption and the usage of those programs along with their porting to other operating systems.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] In December 1991, the **first web server outside Europe** was installed at SLAC (U.S.A.).
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] This was a very important event because it started trans-continental web communications between web browsers and web servers.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] In 1991–1993, CERN web server program continued to be actively developed by the www group, meanwhile, thanks to the availability of its source code and the public specifications of the HTTP protocol, many other implementations of web servers started to be developed.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] In April 1993, CERN issued a public official statement stating that the three components of Web software (the basic line-mode client, the web server and the library of common code), along with their source code, were put in the public domain.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] This statement freed web server developers from any possible legal issue about the development of *derivative work* based on that source code (a threat that in practice never existed).
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] At the beginning of 1994, the most notable among new web servers was NCSA httpd which ran on a variety of Unix-based OSs and could serve *dynamically generated content* by implementing the `POST` HTTP method and the CGI to communicate with external programs.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] These capabilities, along with the multimedia features of NCSA's Mosaic browser (also able to manage HTML FORMs in order to send data to a web server) highlighted the potential of web technology for publishing and distributed computing applications.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] At the beginning of 1995 those patches were all applied to the last release of NCSA source code and, after several tests, the Apache HTTP server project was started.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] At the end of 1994, a new commercial web server, named Netsite, was released with specific features.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] It was the first one of many other similar products that were developed first by Netscape, then also by Sun Microsystems, and finally by Oracle Corporation.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] In mid-1995, the first version of IIS was released by Microsoft for Windows NT OS.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] This marked the entry, in the field of World Wide Web technologies, of a commercial developer and vendor that has played and still is playing a key role on both sides (client and server) of the web.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] In the second half of 1995, CERN and NCSA web servers started to decline (in global percentage usage) because of the widespread adoption of new web servers which had a much faster development cycle along with more features, more fixes applied, and more performances than the previous ones.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] At the end of 1996, there were already over fifty known, different web-server-software programs that were available to everybody who wanted to own an Internet domain name or to host websites.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] Many of them lived only shortly and were replaced by other web servers.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] The publication of RFCs about protocol versions HTTP/1.0 (1996) and HTTP/1.1 (1997, 1999), forced most web servers to comply (not always completely) with those standards.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] The use of TCP/IP persistent connections (HTTP/1.1) required web servers both to increase the maximum number of concurrent connections allowed and to improve their level of scalability.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] Between 1996 and 1999, Netscape Enterprise Server and Microsoft's IIS emerged among the leading commercial options whereas among the freely available and open-source programs Apache HTTP Server held the lead as the preferred server (because of its reliability and its many features).
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] In those years there was also another commercial web server called Zeus (*now discontinued*) that was known as one of the fastest and most scalable web servers available on market, at least till the first decade of 2000s, despite its low percentage of usage.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] Apache resulted in the most used web server from mid-1996 to the end of 2015 when, after a few years of decline, it was surpassed initially by IIS and then by Nginx.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] Afterward IIS dropped to much lower percentages of usage than Apache (see also market share).
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] From 2005–2006, Apache started to improve its speed and its scalability level by introducing new performance features (e.g., event MPM and new content cache).
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] A few years after 2000 started, not only other commercial and highly competitive web servers (e.g., LiteSpeed) but also many other open-source programs such as Hiawatha, Cherokee HTTP server, Lighttpd, Nginx and other derived and related products also available with commercial support emerged.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] Within a year, these changes, on average, nearly tripled the maximum number of persistent connections that web servers had to manage.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] In 2015, RFCs published new protocol version [HTTP/2], and as the implementation of new specifications was not trivial at all, a **dilemma arose among developers of less popular web servers** (e.g., with a percentage of usage lower than 1% ..
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] 2%), about adding or not adding support for that new protocol version.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] In 2020–2021 the HTTP/2 dynamics about its implementation (by top web servers and popular web browsers) were partly replicated after the publication of advanced drafts of future RFC about HTTP/3 protocol.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] The following technical overview should be considered only as an attempt to give a few very *limited examples* about *some* features that may be implemented in a web server and *some* of the tasks that it may perform in order to have a sufficiently wide scenario about the topic.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] A **web server program** plays the role of a server in a client–server model by implementing one or more versions of HTTP protocol, often including the HTTPS secure variant and other features and extensions that are considered useful for its planned usage.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] Although web server programs differ in how they are implemented, most of them offer the following common features.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] These are **basic features** that most web servers usually have.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] A few other more **advanced** and popular **features** (*only a very short selection*) are the following ones.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] Once an HTTP request message has been decoded and verified, its values can be used to determine whether that request can be satisfied or not.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] This requires many other steps, including **security checks**.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] The term *URL normalization* refers to the process of modifying and standardizing a URL in a consistent manner.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] There are several types of normalization that may be performed, including the conversion of the scheme and host to lowercase.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] Among the most important normalizations are the removal of "." and ".." path segments and adding trailing slashes to a non-empty path component.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] One or more configuration files of web server may specify the mapping of parts of **URL path** (e.g., initial parts of file path, filename extension and other path components) to a specific URL handler (file, directory, external program or internal module).
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] Web server programs are able to translate an URL path (all or part of it), that refers to a physical file system path, to an absolute path under the target website's root directory.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] Website's root directory may be specified by a configuration file or by some internal rule of the web server by using the name of the website which is the host part of the URL found in HTTP client request.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] The web server appends the path found in requested URL (HTTP request message) and appends it to the path of the (Host) website root directory.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] On an Apache server, this is commonly `/home/www/website` (on Unix machines, usually it is: `/var/www/website`).
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] See the following examples of how it may result.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] The web server then reads the file, if it exists, and sends a response to the client's web browser.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] The response will describe the content of the file and contain the file itself or an error message will return saying that the file does not exist or its access is forbidden.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] The response will describe the content of the directory (list of contained subdirectories and files) or an error message will return saying that the directory does not exist or its access is forbidden.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] For a *dynamic request* the URL path specified by the client should refer to an existing external program (usually an executable file with a CGI) used by the web server to generate dynamic content.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] The web server executes that program, passing in the path-info and the query string `action=view&orderby=thread&date=2021-10-15` so that the program has the info it needs to run.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] (In this case, it will return an HTML document containing a view of forum entries ordered by thread from October 15, 2021).
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] In addition to this, the web server reads data sent from the external program and resends that data to the client that made the request.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] Once a request has been read, interpreted, and verified, it has to be managed depending on its method, its URL, and its parameters, which may include values of HTTP headers.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] That kind of content is called *static* because usually it is not changed by the web server when it is sent to clients and because it remains the same until it is modified (file modification) by some program.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] Response of static file content can be sped up by a **file cache**.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] Most used names for static index files are: `index.html`, `index.htm` and `Default.htm`.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] If a web server program receives a client request message with an URL whose path matches the file name of an existing *file* and that file is accessible by web server program and its attributes match internal rules of web server program, then web server program can send that file to client.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] Usually, for security reasons, most web server programs are pre-configured to serve only regular files or to avoid to use *special file types* like device files, along with symbolic links or hard links to them.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] The aim is to avoid undesirable side effects when serving static web resources.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] If a web server program is capable of **serving dynamic content** and it has been configured to do so, then it is able to communicate with the proper internal module or external program (associated with the requested URL path) in order to pass to it the parameters of the client request.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] After that, the web server program reads from it its data response (that it has generated, often on the fly) and then it resends it to the client program who made the request.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] In order to be able to communicate with its internal modules or external programs, a web server program must have implemented one or more of the many available **gateway interfaces** (see also Web Server Gateway Interfaces used for dynamic content).
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] The three **standard** and historical **gateway interfaces** are the following ones.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] An external CGI program is run by web server program for each dynamic request, then web server program reads from it the generated data response and then resends it to client.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] An external FastCGI program (it usually is a process) is started once by web server program or by some other program or process and then it waits for a network connection which is established permanently by web server; through that connection are sent the request parameters and read data responses.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] A web server program may be capable to manage the dynamic generation (on the fly) of a **directory index list** of files and sub-directories.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] If it cannot be generated an error is returned.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] Usage of dynamically generated *directory listings* is usually avoided or limited to a few selected directories of a website because that generation takes much more OS resources than sending a static index page.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] The main usage of *directory listings* is to allow the download of files (usually when their names, sizes, modification date-times or file attributes may change randomly and frequently) *as they are, without requiring to provide further information to requesting user*.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] In practice whenever there is content that may vary, depending on one or more parameters contained in client request or in configuration settings, then, usually, it is generated dynamically.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] Web server programs are able to send response messages as replies to client request messages.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] An error response message may be sent because a request message could not be successfully read or decoded or analyzed or executed.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] NOTE: the following sections are reported only as examples to help to understand what a web server, more or less, does; these sections are by any means neither exhaustive nor complete.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] When an error response or message is received by a client browser, then if it is related to the main user request (e.g., an URL of a web resource such as a web page) then usually that error message is shown in some browser window or message.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] Example 1: a URL path points to a **directory** name but it does not have a final slash '/' so web server sends a redirect to client in order to instruct it to redo the request with the fixed path name.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] Example 2: a whole set of documents has been **moved inside website** in order to reorganize their file system paths.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] Example 3: a whole set of documents has been **moved to a new website** and now it is mandatory to use secure HTTPS connections to access them.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] Above examples are only a few of the possible kind of redirections.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] A web server program is able to reply to a valid client request message with a successful message, optionally containing requested **web resource data**.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] If web resource data is sent back to client, then it can be **static content** or **dynamic content** depending on how it has been retrieved (from a file or from the output of some program or module).
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] In order to speed up web server responses by lowering average HTTP response times and hardware resources used, many popular web servers implement one or more content caches, each one specialized in a content category.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] In practice, nowadays, many web server programs include their own *userland* **file cache**, tailored for a web server usage and using their specific implementation and parameters.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] The wide spread adoption of RAID and fast solid-state drives (storage hardware with very high I/O speed) has slightly reduced but of course not eliminated the advantage of having a file cache incorporated in a web server.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] Dynamic content, output by an internal module or an external program, may not always change very frequently (given a unique URL with keys or parameters) and so, maybe for a while (e.g., from one second to several hours or more), the resulting output can be cached in RAM or even on a fast disk.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] Anyway, in most cases those kind of caches are implemented by external servers (e.g., reverse proxy) or by storing dynamic data output in separate computers, managed by specific applications (e.g., memcached), in order to not compete for hardware resources (CPU, RAM, disks) with web servers.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] A web server software can be either incorporated into the OS and executed in kernel space, or it can be executed in user space (like other regular applications).
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] Web servers that run in user-mode have to ask the system for permission to use more memory or more CPU resources.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] Not only do these requests to the kernel take time, but they might not always be satisfied because the system reserves resources for its own usage and has the responsibility to share hardware resources with all the other running applications.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] Executing in user mode can also mean using more buffer or data copies (between user-space and kernel-space) which can lead to a decrease in the performance of a user-mode web server.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] Nowadays almost all web server software is executed in user mode (because many of the aforementioned small disadvantages have been overcome by faster hardware, new OS versions, much faster OS system calls and new optimized web server software).
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] See also comparison of web server software to discover which of them run in kernel mode or in user mode (also referred as kernel space or user space).
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] In other words, a **web server should always be very responsive**, even under high load of web traffic, in order to keep **total user's wait** (sum of browser time + network time + **web server response time**) for a response **as low as possible**.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] Among the operating conditions, the **number** (1 ..
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] *n*) of **concurrent client connections** used during a test is an important parameter because it allows to correlate the **concurrency level** supported by web server with results of the tested performance metrics.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] ... used to implement a web server program, **can bias a lot the performances** and in particular the **scalability level** that can be achieved under **heavy load** or when using high end hardware (many CPUs, disks and lots of RAM).
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] In practice some web server software models may require more OS resources (specially more CPUs and more RAM) than others to be able to work well and so to achieve target performances.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p01] Performances of a web server are typically benchmarked by using one or more of the available automated load testing tools.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p02] When a web server is near to or over its load limits, it gets **overloaded** and so it may become **unresponsive**.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p02] Below are the latest statistics of the market share of all sites of the top web servers on the Internet by Netcraft.
[src:aiohttp-client/web-server-p02] NOTE: (*) percentage rounded to integer number, because its decimal values are not publicly reported by source page (only its rounded value is reported in graph).
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] WebSocket is distinct from HTTP used to serve most webpages.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] Although they are different, RFC 6455 states that WebSocket "is designed to work over HTTP ports 443 and 80 as well as to support HTTP proxies and intermediaries", making the WebSocket protocol compatible with HTTP.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] To achieve compatibility, the WebSocket handshake uses the HTTP Upgrade header to change from the HTTP protocol to the WebSocket protocol.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] The WebSocket protocol enables full-duplex interaction between a web browser (or other client application) and a web server with lower overhead than half-duplex alternatives such as HTTP polling, facilitating real-time data transfer from and to the server.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] This is achieved by providing a standardized way for the server to send content to the client without being first requested by the client, and allowing messages to be exchanged while keeping the connection open.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] In this way, a two-way ongoing conversation can take place between the client and the server.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] The communications are usually done over TCP port number 443 (or 80 in the case of unsecured connections), which is beneficial for environments that block non-web Internet connections using a firewall.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] Additionally, WebSocket enables streams of messages on top of TCP.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] TCP alone deals with streams of bytes with no inherent concept of a message.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] Similar two-way browser–server communications have been achieved in non-standardized ways using stopgap technologies such as Comet or Adobe Flash Player.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] Most browsers support the protocol, including Google Chrome, Firefox, Microsoft Edge, Internet Explorer, Safari and Opera.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] The WebSocket protocol specification defines `ws` (WebSocket) and `wss` (WebSocket Secure) as two new uniform resource identifier (URI) schemes that are used for unencrypted and encrypted connections respectively.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] Apart from the scheme name and fragment (i.e.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] `#` is not supported), the rest of the URI components are defined to use URI generic syntax.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] WebSocket was first referenced as TCPConnection in the HTML5 specification, as a placeholder for a TCP-based socket API.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] In June 2008, a series of discussions were led by Michael Carter that resulted in the first version of the protocol known as WebSocket.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] Before WebSocket, port 80 full-duplex communication was attainable using Comet channels; however, Comet implementation is nontrivial, and due to the TCP handshake and HTTP header overhead, it is inefficient for small messages.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] The WebSocket protocol aims to solve these problems without compromising the security assumptions of the web.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] The name "WebSocket" was coined by Ian Hickson and Michael Carter shortly thereafter through collaboration on the #whatwg IRC chat room, and subsequently authored for inclusion in the HTML5 specification by Ian Hickson.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] In December 2009, Google Chrome 4 was the first browser to ship full support for the standard, with WebSocket enabled by default.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] Development of the WebSocket protocol was subsequently moved from the W3C and WHATWG group to the IETF in February 2010, and authored for two revisions under Ian Hickson.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] After the protocol was shipped and enabled by default in multiple browsers, the RFC 6455 was finalized under Ian Fette in December 2011.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] RFC 7692 introduced compression extension to WebSocket using the DEFLATE algorithm on a per-message basis.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] A web application (e.g. web browser) may use the `WebSocket` interface to maintain bidirectional communications with a WebSocket server.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] **Frame-based message** exchange: data, ping and pong messages.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] **Closing handshake**: close message (request then echoed in response).
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] The client sends an **HTTP request** (**method** **GET**, **version ≥ 1.1**) and the server returns an **HTTP response** with **status code 101** (*Switching Protocols*) on success.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] HTTP and WebSocket clients can connect to a server using the same port because the opening handshake uses HTTP.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] Sending additional HTTP headers (that are not in the table below) is allowed.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] After the *Switching Protocols* HTTP response, the opening handshake is complete, the HTTP protocol stops being used, and communication switches to a binary frame-based protocol.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] The following Python code generates a random `Sec-WebSocket-Key`.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] The following Python code calculates `Sec-WebSocket-Accept` using `Sec-WebSocket-Key` from the example request above.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] `Sec-WebSocket-Key` and `Sec-WebSocket-Accept` are intended to prevent a caching proxy from re-sending a previous WebSocket conversation, and does not provide any authentication, privacy, or integrity.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] Though some servers accept a short `Sec-WebSocket-Key`, many modern servers will reject the request with error "invalid Sec-WebSocket-Key header".
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] After the opening handshake, the client and server can, at any time, send **data messages** (text or binary) and **control messages** (*Close*, *Ping*, *Pong*) to each other.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] A message is composed of **one frame if unfragmented** or **at least two frames if fragmented**.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] A **client must mask** all frames sent to the server.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] A **server must not mask** any frames sent to the client.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] Frame masking applies **XOR between the payload and the masking key**.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] The following pseudocode describes the algorithm used to both mask and unmask a frame.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] The `permessage-deflate` extension allows data messages to be compressed using the DEFLATE algorithm.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] For example, during the opening handshake, the client and server may use the following header to enable the extension.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] The `RSV1` field of the first frame of a data message must be set to indicate the payload data is compressed.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] Note: `recv()` returns up to the amount of bytes requested.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] For readability, the code ignores that, thus it may fail in non-ideal network conditions.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] A secure version of the WebSocket protocol is implemented in Firefox 6, Safari 6, Google Chrome 14, Opera 12.10 and Internet Explorer 10.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] A detailed protocol test suite report lists the conformance of those browsers to specific protocol aspects.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] An older, less secure version of the protocol was implemented in Opera 11 and Safari 5, as well as the mobile version of Safari in iOS 4.2.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] The BlackBerry Browser in OS7 implements WebSockets.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] Because of vulnerabilities, it was disabled in Firefox 4 and 5, and Opera 11.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] Using browser developer tools, developers can inspect the WebSocket handshake as well as the WebSocket frames.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] ASP.NET Core have support for WebSockets using the `app.UseWebSockets();` middleware.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] Unlike regular cross-domain HTTP requests, WebSocket requests are not restricted by the same-origin policy.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] It is better to use tokens or similar protection mechanisms to authenticate the WebSocket connection when sensitive (private) data is being transferred over the WebSocket.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] A live example of vulnerability was seen in 2020 in the form of Cable Haunt.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] WebSocket protocol client implementations try to detect whether the user agent is configured to use a proxy when connecting to destination host and port, and if it is, uses HTTP CONNECT method to set up a persistent tunnel.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] The WebSocket protocol is unaware of proxy servers and firewalls.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] Some proxy servers are transparent and work fine with WebSocket; others will prevent WebSocket from working correctly, causing the connection to fail.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] In some cases, additional proxy-server configuration may be required, and certain proxy servers may need to be upgraded to support WebSocket.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] If unencrypted WebSocket traffic flows through an explicit or a transparent proxy server without WebSockets support, the connection will likely fail.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] If an encrypted WebSocket connection is used, then the use of Transport Layer Security (TLS) in the WebSocket Secure connection ensures that an `HTTP CONNECT` command is issued when the browser is configured to use an explicit proxy server.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] This sets up a tunnel, which provides low-level end-to-end TCP communication through the HTTP proxy, between the WebSocket Secure client and the WebSocket server.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] In the case of transparent proxy servers, the browser is unaware of the proxy server, so no `HTTP CONNECT` is sent.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] However, since the wire traffic is encrypted, intermediate transparent proxy servers may simply allow the encrypted traffic through, so there is a much better chance that the WebSocket connection will succeed if WebSocket Secure is used.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] Using encryption is not free of resource cost, but often provides the highest success rate, since it would be travelling through a secure tunnel.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] A mid-2010 draft (version hixie-76) broke compatibility with reverse proxies and gateways by including eight bytes of key data after the headers, but not advertising that data in a `Content-Length: 8` header.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] This data was not forwarded by all intermediates, which could lead to protocol failure.
[src:aiohttp-client/websocket] More recent drafts (e.g., hybi-09) put the key data in a `Sec-WebSocket-Key` header, solving this problem.
